    "definition": "An act break is the structural division of a television episode into segments, corresponding to commercial breaks on advertising-driven networks. A one-hour drama is typically broken into four to six acts, each ending on a cliffhanger, turn, or escalation of stakes designed to make the audience return after the break. The end of an act is also called an Act-Out.\n\nNetworks and formats differ: broadcast dramas have historically used four acts, with many now using five or six; premium cable and streaming shows may use fewer or no formal act breaks. Unlike in feature screenplays, each act is labeled and usually preceded by a page break in a television script.\n\n### Act markers\n\nAct markers are explicit labels inserted into a television script to designate the beginning of each act, typically accompanied by a page break. Unlike feature screenplays, where act divisions are structural conventions invisible on the page, TV scripts make acts visible as formatted elements. Each act opens with a centred or underlined heading — \"ACT ONE\", \"ACT TWO\", and so on — set off by a hard page break from the preceding act. This formatting is both a production convention and a practical signal to the reader about where act break moments occur and how the episode is parcelled across commercial interruptions.\n\nThe number of acts varies by network and format: broadcast drama commonly runs four or five acts, some procedurals use six or seven, while cable and streaming series may label only two or three — or treat act divisions as purely structural rather than typographical. In any case, the markers serve as a navigational grid, making the episode's rhythm legible at a glance and helping the [[Writers' room]] track pacing across the full run of an episode.\n\nSee also [[Cliffhanger]], [[Teaser]], [[Story structure]].",
