    "definition": "An arc is a trajectory of change — the movement of a character, relationship, or storyline from one state to another across the span of a story. At every scale, the baseline requirement is the same: if a character or situation is identical at the end to what it was at the beginning, no arc has occurred. The distinction between *change* and *growth* is useful here: a character heading in the wrong direction must change course, while one already pointed right must grow stronger to reach their goal.\n\n**Character arc.** The character arc describes the internal transformation of a person — what they fear, believe, or are capable of at the start differs from what they are at the end. It is a journey from fear to courage, from living an emotionally safe but unfulfilled existence to risking everything to find one's destiny, expressible as a \"before and after.\" This change may be hard-won growth, a moral collapse, or — in tragic structures — a refusal to change that costs the character everything. Some writers prefer the term *character journey* (Landau) to emphasize that the arc is not just the end state but the path traveled. Not every character needs one; a steadfast character who remains constant while the world shifts around them is a legitimate and sometimes essential choice. In closed-ended [[Format|sitcom]]s, characters often do not arc at all — their flaws persist as the engine of comedy. \"Character development\" and \"character evolution\" are broader terms used in general discussion; they describe arc-related growth but are not precise synonyms for the arc itself.\n\nA key tool for constructing the character arc is the **broken compass** — the wrong-way guidance system a hero obsessively follows along their spiritual journey. Generated by the character's [[Shard of glass]] and expressed through their [[Fatal flaw]], it manifests as misguided \"mission statements\" or mantras (framed with \"always\" or \"never\") that encode a flawed philosophy. The broken compass is the writer's secret weapon for character-driven storytelling: the hero's reactions are determined by following this malfunctioning guide rather than what would actually serve them. See also [[Need (character)]].\n\n**Season arc.** A season arc is the overarching narrative or character development that unfolds across a complete season — the larger trajectory that individual episodes serve and advance. Strong series create new scenarios and settings for each season that continue the [[Compelling crisis]] with higher stakes, a new setting, and a unique threat. A character arc often *is* the season arc, particularly in character-led drama.\n\n**Series arc.** A series arc is the narrative or character transformation that unfolds across the entire run of the series — the steepest and longest arc of change. The best dramas offer a series arc that slowly answers a major dramatic question or traces the steps toward an inevitable end. It is established in the [[Pilot]] and builds throughout; the series finale contains its climax or resolution.\n\n**Pilot arc.** A pilot arc is the character arc the protagonist undergoes specifically within the pilot — a compressed version of the larger journey the series will explore. It establishes the character's starting point and demonstrates their capacity for change.\n\nAll three scales — pilot, season, series — can coexist and should each be expressible as a discrete \"before and after.\" In pitching contexts, writers are typically asked to sketch at least the first-season arc to demonstrate that the [[Story engine]] can sustain itself — that the premise has [[Legs]] beyond the [[Pilot]]. Within a single episode or act, the same logic applies in miniature: a scene or subplot carries its own local arc, a small rise and fall that contributes to the larger shape. The choice of which scale to foreground commits the writers' room to a corresponding structure: a tightly resolved pilot arc signals an episodic or procedural register; a long, deliberately unresolved series arc signals a serial one.\n\n**Save-the-Cat structural beats.** Snyder, Calvisi, and Landau name specific positions along the arc — engineered moments of rising and falling action across the second and third acts. They are not the arc itself but places where structural pressure tends to land.\n\n**Hero committed.** End of Act One. The protagonist crosses into the new reality and can no longer retreat to prior circumstances. The inciting incident creates pressure; this beat seals the door.\n\n**Midpoint (false victory / false defeat).** The hinge at the halfway mark of a script or episode. Either a fleeting taste of victory before it is snatched away (false victory) or apparent failure that drives a harder push (false defeat). The protagonist's goal is clarified or threatened; a new dramatic question is raised. Often paired with a deadline (see [[Ticking time clock]]). Calvisi calls this the «hero succeeds—almost» beat — a controlled release of tension that makes the subsequent collapse land harder than a straightforward setback. In multi-A/B story TV structure the midpoint usually pivots the «A» story most visibly; in episodic formats it is sometimes called the act-two act-out.\n\n**Bad guys close in.** Second half of act two. Pressure on the protagonist intensifies from multiple directions simultaneously — external (rivals, institutions, physical danger) and internal (doubt, guilt, self-destruction). The phase ends when the situation reaches its lowest point, forcing the character to make a decisive choice.\n\n**Big risk / declaration of war.** Structural turning point in which the protagonist commits to a bold or irreversible course of action — open conflict with the opposing force, a point of no return. Stakes rise; the protagonist stops reacting and starts initiating.\n\n**All is lost (worst point).** The lowest moment in the arc, roughly three-quarters through the story. The protagonist's worst fear is realised; defeat appears certain. A common marker is a «whiff of death» — actual loss of life or its credible threat. Functions as the third-act act-out in features and as the act-break cliffhanger before the final commercial break in episodic TV. Also called the **second-act turning point** in Calvisi's framework — the moment of maximum crisis before the final push toward resolution.\n\n**Dark night of the soul.** The beat of despair and mourning that follows «all is lost». The character is not yet acting — they are grieving. The old identity, belief, or goal has been stripped away without a new one yet in place. Productive rather than merely bleak: meaningful learning typically occurs here, preparing the character to act differently in the climax.\n\n**Going all in.** Decisive, character-defining commitment — fully investing in a course of action with no easy retreat. Less about external plot logistics, more about psychological ownership: the protagonist takes control rather than reacting to circumstances.\n\n**Assumption of power.** Act-three beat. The protagonist fully steps into their own strength — discards hesitation, commits completely, and acts from a place of genuine agency rather than reaction. The dramatic payoff of everything the episode has been building.\n\n**Declaration of war & all is lost (act four act-out).** In four-act TV drama, the act-four beat in which the protagonist commits to a specific high-risk method of defeating the antagonistic forces — only for that surge of power to collapse into their lowest point. The pairing is intentional: the declaration creates the conditions for the collapse. The higher the apparent win, the more devastating the reversal.",
