    "definition": "The back nine refers to the final nine episodes of a traditional 22-episode network season, following the initial thirteen-episode order.\n\nIn a full-season pickup, the network does not always commit to all 22 episodes at once. Even when a series receives a nominal full-season order, the decision to produce the back nine is often contingent on how the first thirteen perform in the ratings. A weak midseason showing can result in the back nine being pulled, effectively shortening the season — or ending the series. This makes the thirteen-episode midpoint a significant internal pressure point for showrunners and the [[Writers' room]], who may be breaking back-nine stories before knowing whether those episodes will ever be made.\n\nThe term is a borrowing from golf, where the back nine refers to the second half of an 18-hole course.",
