    "definition": "Backstory is the history that exists before the story begins — incidents, relationships, and formative experiences that shaped who a character is when the audience first meets them.\n\nWriters develop backstory in depth during the drafting process, but most of it should remain invisible on screen. Only the portion of backstory that, if withheld, would block the audience's emotional identification with a character needs to surface in the narrative. Revealing too much too early — heavy setup and explanatory detail before any consequences are established — is one of the most common structural mistakes in a pitch or script. The test is always the \"so what?\" factor: does this information change how the audience feels about what is happening right now?\n\nBackstory is distinct from [[Story DNA]] (the thematic premise baked into the series) and from [[World building]] (the external rules and texture of the storyworld). It belongs specifically to character: the private past that drives present [[Want (character)|want]], behaviour, and wound.",
