    "definition": "A **beat** is a discrete unit of storytelling — a single moment, exchange, or step that moves a scene or story forward. The word operates across several levels of granularity, from the smallest pause in a scene to the highest-order structural landmarks of an entire episode or series. A **beat sheet** is the document that collects these units into a sequential list — the major events and decisions that make up a story from beginning to end, often organised by act, forming the structural skeleton from which a teleplay grows. See also [[Breaking story]], [[Breakdown]], [[Story structure]].\n\nThe word *beat* itself works at two distinct levels. At the **scene level**, a beat is the smallest dramatic unit within a scene: a line of dialogue, an exchange organised around one thought, or a described action. When that thought resolves, the scene moves to the next beat. Directors and actors routinely break scenes into beats this way to analyse intention and pacing. At the **story level**, beats are the high-level structural moves that map out how a narrative assembles itself without yet filling in every detail — assembly instructions that capture what happens and in what order, leaving granular texture for the actual writing.\n\nWithin story-level beats, a further distinction is useful. **Pillar beats** are the handful of anchor moments that hold the overall structure together — the non-negotiable turning points that everything else is built around. Remove one and the story collapses; they define the shape of the narrative the way tent-poles define a tent. **Signpost beats** are the broader set of structural landmarks that define the shape of an act or episode. Supporting beats fill the space between them, providing texture and momentum without carrying the same load-bearing function. Fast-moving genres tend to compress or skip transitional beats entirely in favour of momentum; slower, more character-driven formats may develop the connective tissue between pillars in considerable detail.\n\nThe beat sheet as a document sits at the intersection of these levels. In a [[TV pitch]] or [[Springboards]] document it is how a writer demonstrates that a concept has been thought through — that it can sustain scenes, not just a premise. The related term **outline** (or *beat outline*) describes the same sequential list in a more formal production context: the semi-standardised deliverable that sits between [[Writers' room]] work and the first draft, typically the earliest document submitted to a network or streamer for notes and approval, and the document that generates a payment and formal \"story by\" credit in many jurisdictions. Where a distinction is drawn, a beat outline may be slightly more granular than a plain scene list — naming the dramatic beat *within* the scene rather than just the scene itself — but in common usage the two labels describe the same deliverable.\n\nIn practice, the choice of how finely to articulate beats depends on where a project sits in development. When breaking a [[Story engine]] early, identifying the four or five pillar beats comes first — before dialogue, before texture, before subplot — to confirm that the concept has [[Legs]] beyond its premise. Signpost and scene-level beats are then built outward from those anchors, and the result is the beat sheet or outline that a room, a buyer, or a network can respond to. The level of detail expected scales with the stage: a pitch may need only pillar beats; a production outline must account for every scene.",
