    "definition": "There are two documents called a bible: the **pitch bible**, used to sell a series, and the **show bible**, used to run it once it is in production. When someone says \"the bible\" with no qualifier, they usually mean the pitch bible. The show bible (sometimes called *series bible* or *production bible*) is a later document that lives inside the [[Writers' room]] and is consulted only after a greenlight.\n\n**Pitch bible — the selling document.** Written before the series is commissioned. Its job is to prove the idea has [[Legs]]: that it can sustain many episodes, not just a [[Pilot]]. Sent to networks, producers, and investors as proof-of-concept. It contains a synopsis of the series describing its [[Premise]] and style, full character details for the regulars, and storylines in whatever number and depth the producer or network requires. In practice no two pitch bibles look the same. Length and shape are dictated by what the producer asks for and how much of the idea the writer needs to put on paper to sell it. See [bible anatomy](https://birdinthetree.github.io/bible-anatomy.html) for examples.\n\nThe pitch bible itself comes in several lengths, all serving the same selling function:\n\n- **Long-form pitch bible** — anywhere from 10 to 85 pages. Used when the producer wants the full case for the show. Synopsis, characters, story engine, season arcs, sample storylines, look-and-feel.\n- **Mini-bible** — a 5-page distillation of the same material. Used when the buyer wants speed, not depth.\n- **TV pitch** — a 5- to 10-page selling document containing everything a studio or network would need: logline, format, characters, [[Story engine]], world, theme, season arc. Self-contained: enough to convey the full potential of the series without a complete pilot script.\n- **Pitch document** — a written companion to a finished pilot script that forecasts what happens in episode 2 and beyond. Used to demonstrate proof-of-concept when the script alone cannot show the show's legs. Distinct from the TV pitch in that it travels alongside the pilot, not instead of it.\n\nThese names overlap in industry usage; the same material can be reshaped into any of them depending on what a producer asks for. The [[Elevator pitch]] is the spoken counterpart, under two minutes, never on paper.\n\n**Show bible — the production document.** A separate document that exists once the show is greenlit and in production. A living internal guide recording the show's essential components: [[Premise]], backstory, full character breakdowns, and rules specific to the series (e.g. \"never write a scene without a regular in it\"). Writers brought into the room must follow it. It is updated as the show evolves so new writers stay consistent with what has already aired. In practice the pitch bible often becomes the seed of the show bible — the same skeleton, kept current.",
