    "definition": "Braided narratives is a structural approach in which two or more storylines run in parallel across an episode or series, interweaving rather than following a single through-line.\n\nThe technique is common in serialised drama and limited series, where the format allows sustained attention to multiple protagonists or timelines. Stories need not share equal weight: one strand may serve as the primary engine while others deepen [[Theme]] or complicate [[Stakes]]. What makes them *braided* rather than merely episodic is that the strands actively inform each other — a development in one thread recontextualises events in another. Flashback structures are a natural companion to braiding, since non-linear timelines multiply the points at which strands can intersect.\n\nBraided narratives are distinct from the conventional A/B/C [[Subplot]] model of procedural television, where secondary plots are subordinate and often resolved within the same episode. In a braided structure, no strand is obliged to resolve on the episode's clock; instead, each carries its own momentum across the series arc. This places additional pressure on the [[Story engine]] and on the [[Writers' room]] to maintain clarity about whose [[Want (character)|want]] is driving each strand at any given moment.",
