    "definition": "*Breakdown* carries two distinct meanings in television, depending on context.\n\n**Scene breakdown — the structural document.**\nA scene-by-scene account of an episode's action, written in present tense. Each entry identifies whether the location is interior or exterior, where and when the scene takes place, and which characters appear. It is more granular than an outline but less fully realised than a draft script — it maps the drama beat by beat so that the shape of the episode is clear before dialogue is written. In a typical production schedule a writer produces the scene breakdown in the week following the story conference, before moving into full script. See also [[Breakdown]].\n\n**Casting breakdown — the industry document.**\nIn the casting context, a breakdown is a written description of a role in a pilot or series, prepared by a casting director and approved by the producers, then circulated through a breakdown service to agents and managers so that representation knows which roles are being cast and what type of talent to submit. It is a purely logistical document and has nothing to do with story structure.\n\nWhen someone in a [[Writers' room]] says \"let's do a breakdown,\" they almost always mean the structural document. When a casting director or agent uses the word, they mean the role description.",
