    "ru": "Catalyst",
    "ready": true,
    "en": "Catalyst",
    "clusters": [],
    "aliases": [
      "catalyst",
      "catalyst character",
      "catalyst (teaser act-out)",
      "inciting incident",
      "triggering incident",
      "character inciting event",
      "inciting action",
      "inciting event (or inciting incident)",
      "inciting incident (act one beat)",
      "disturbance",
      "triggering crisis",
      "normality",
      "springboards",
      "springboard",
      "recurring catalyst",
      "episodic catalyst",
      "episode trigger"
    ],
    "definition": "The **inciting incident** (also called the **catalyst**) is the event or reveal that upsets the established order, raises the stakes, and launches the main dramatic action of an episode or story. It stops the protagonist in their tracks, triggers their goal, and opens the door to a new journey — leaving the audience with an urgent need to keep watching and a compelling dramatic question still unanswered. The two terms are used interchangeably across most of the literature, referring to the same structural beat: the moment the story truly begins.\n\nWhere the terms do diverge, it is along a positional distinction within the act structure. Some authors (notably Calvisi) reserve **catalyst** for the *Teaser Act-Out* — the hook at the very end of the pre-title sequence — where it functions as a tantalising first disruption, a hint at the dramatic scenario to come. **Inciting incident**, in this usage, names the beat that arrives in Act One proper and fully launches the A story, either setting it in motion for the first time or, if it has already begun, accelerating it forward with new urgency. The catalyst breaks the surface; the inciting incident pulls the protagonist fully under.\n\nIn practice, whether a writers' room treats these as one beat or two depends on the show's structure. A series with a substantial Teaser may find it useful to distinguish the two — the catalyst as an immediate hook, the inciting incident as the deeper commitment to the episode's central problem. A tighter, cold-open-light structure may collapse them into a single story-launching event. Either way, the essential function is the same: something surprising and high-conflict happens, and the world the protagonist knew is no longer available to them.\n\n**Recurring catalyst (in series template).** When the same kind of triggering event occurs every episode within a [[Franchise]], it is given different names depending on the author: Aronson calls it the **disturbance** — «the cataclysmic event that triggers the main plot of each episode» — while Calvisi calls it **springboards**, «the recurring catalysts that propel dramatic conflicts each episode». The mechanic is identical to the inciting incident; the distinction is repetition. A police procedural's weekly crime, a medical drama's patient-of-the-week, a courtroom show's case-of-the-week — each is a fresh inciting incident operating as a built-in feature of the [[Story engine]].",
    "notes": "",
    "comments": []
