    "ru": "Peak tv",
    "ready": true,
    "en": "Peak tv",
    "clusters": [],
    "aliases": [
      "peak tv"
    ],
    "definition": "Peak TV refers to the era of unprecedented volume in scripted television, in which the sheer number of series produced and distributed across broadcast, cable, and streaming platforms reached saturation point.\n\nThe term carries both a descriptive and an anxious meaning: more shows are being made than at any previous moment, yet the landmark series that defined the era's reputation have largely concluded their runs, raising questions about whether the creative high-water mark has passed along with the quantitative one. For writers, Peak TV represents both opportunity — more commissions, more platforms, more formats — and intensified competition for audience attention. It is the industrial context that makes a sharp [[TV pitch]], a distinctive [[Story engine]], and clear [[Stakes]] more essential than ever.",
    "notes": "",
    "comments": []
